Alright, this is a pure design exercise — the claude_resonance project is unrelated. Let me build this from first principles in Dart, since that's your world.

## The Design

Here's what I find genuinely beautiful about this problem: music has *exactly* the same compositional structure as a lot of things in programming (parsers, UI layouts, animations), but with richer semantics. The two-axis composition — sequential and parallel — is the skeleton everything hangs off of.

### Layer 1: Pitch as Algebra

Most libraries represent pitch as an integer (MIDI number) or a string (`"C#4"`). Both are wrong. Pitch has *structure*: a pitch class (the note name, independent of octave) and an octave. And crucially, **C♯ and D♭ are different musical concepts that happen to sound the same**. We should respect that.

```dart
/// The 7 natural note names. Sharps/flats are modifiers, not separate names.
enum NoteName { C, D, E, F, G, A, B }

/// Modification to a natural note.
enum Accidental {
  doubleFlat(-2),
  flat(-1),
  natural(0),
  sharp(1),
  doubleSharp(2);

  final int semitoneOffset;
  const Accidental(this.semitoneOffset);
}

/// A note name without octave — C#, Db, E, etc.
/// Preserves enharmonic spelling: C# ≠ Db even though they're the same pitch.
class PitchClass {
  final NoteName name;
  final Accidental accidental;

  const PitchClass(this.name, [this.accidental = Accidental.natural]);

  /// The chromatic index (0–11), where C = 0.
  int get chromaticIndex =>
      _naturalSemitones[name.index] + accidental.semitoneOffset;

  /// Enharmonic equivalence — same sound, different spelling.
  bool isEnharmonicWith(PitchClass other) =>
      chromaticIndex % 12 == other.chromaticIndex % 12;

  static const _naturalSemitones = [0, 2, 4, 5, 7, 9, 11]; // C D E F G A B
}

/// A pitch: pitch class + octave. Middle C = Pitch(C, 4).
class Pitch implements Comparable<Pitch> {
  final PitchClass pitchClass;
  final int octave;

  const Pitch(this.pitchClass, this.octave);

  /// MIDI note number. Useful for computation, not for identity.
  int get midi => (octave + 1) * 12 + pitchClass.chromaticIndex;

  /// Apply an interval to get a new pitch.
  Pitch operator +(Interval interval) => interval.applyTo(this);

  @override
  int compareTo(Pitch other) => midi.compareTo(other.midi);
}
```

### Layer 2: Intervals as Transformations

This is where it gets interesting. An interval isn't just "5 semitones" — it's a *transformation* on pitch space. A perfect fifth and a diminished sixth are both 7 semitones, but they mean different things musically.

```dart
/// The diatonic "size" of an interval — unison, second, third, etc.
enum IntervalNumber {
  unison(0), second(1), third(2), fourth(3),
  fifth(4), sixth(5), seventh(6), octave(7);

  final int diatonicSteps;
  const IntervalNumber(this.diatonicSteps);
}

enum IntervalQuality { diminished, minor, perfect, major, augmented }

/// A musical interval: the *relationship* between two pitches.
/// Intervals compose: a major third + a minor third = a perfect fifth.
class Interval {
  final IntervalNumber number;
  final IntervalQuality quality;

  const Interval(this.number, this.quality);

  int get semitones => _baseSemitones[number]! + _qualityOffset;

  /// Compose intervals: go up a third, then up another third.
  Interval operator +(Interval other) => _composeIntervals(this, other);

  /// Invert: a major 3rd inverts to a minor 6th.
  Interval get inversion => _invertInterval(this);

  Pitch applyTo(Pitch pitch) { /* transpose logic */ }

  // Common intervals as constants — reads like music theory.
  static const minorSecond = Interval(IntervalNumber.second, IntervalQuality.minor);
  static const majorThird = Interval(IntervalNumber.third, IntervalQuality.major);
  static const perfectFifth = Interval(IntervalNumber.fifth, IntervalQuality.perfect);
  static const octave = Interval(IntervalNumber.octave, IntervalQuality.perfect);
  // ... etc
}
```

### Layer 3: Rhythm as Duration Algebra

Rhythm is its own dimension, independent of pitch. The key insight: durations are **rationals**, not floats. A quarter note is exactly 1/4 of a whole note. Tuplets are just different rationals.

```dart
/// A rhythmic duration as an exact fraction of a whole note.
/// Quarter = 1/4, dotted quarter = 3/8, triplet eighth = 1/12.
class Duration implements Comparable<Duration> {
  final int numerator;
  final int denominator;

  const Duration(this.numerator, this.denominator);

  /// Durations add when notes are tied.
  Duration operator +(Duration other) => _addFractions(this, other);

  /// Dotting multiplies by 3/2.
  Duration get dotted => Duration(numerator * 3, denominator * 2);

  /// Tuplet: fit [n] notes in the space of [inSpaceOf].
  Duration tuplet(int n, int inSpaceOf) =>
      Duration(numerator * inSpaceOf, denominator * n);

  static const whole     = Duration(1, 1);
  static const half      = Duration(1, 2);
  static const quarter   = Duration(1, 4);
  static const eighth    = Duration(1, 8);
  static const sixteenth = Duration(1, 16);
}
```

### Layer 4: Expression — Dynamics and Articulation

These are the adjectives and adverbs of music.

```dart
/// Discrete dynamic levels.
enum DynamicLevel {
  ppp, pp, p, mp, mf, f, ff, fff;

  /// Numeric velocity (0.0–1.0) for when you need it.
  double get velocity => index / (values.length - 1);
}

/// How a note is attacked and sustained.
enum Articulation { legato, tenuto, normal, portato, staccato, staccatissimo, accent, marcato }

/// Everything about *how* a note sounds, separate from *what* note it is.
class Expression {
  final DynamicLevel dynamic;
  final Articulation articulation;
  // Could add: ornaments, technique markings, etc.

  const Expression({
    this.dynamic = DynamicLevel.mf,
    this.articulation = Articulation.normal,
  });
}
```

### Layer 5: The Core — `Music` as a Composable Tree

Here's the heart of it. `Music` is a **sealed algebraic type** with four variants. Everything else is syntactic sugar over these four constructors:

```dart
/// The fundamental music type. Everything composes from these four cases.
///
/// This is the key insight: music is a tree with two axes of composition
/// (sequential and parallel), leaves (notes/rests), and metadata overlays.
sealed class Music {
  const Music();

  // ---- The four constructors ----

  /// A single pitched event: the atom of music.
  const factory Music.note(Pitch pitch, Duration duration, {Expression expression}) = Note;

  /// Silence with duration: as important as sound.
  const factory Music.rest(Duration duration) = Rest;

  /// Sequential composition: play these one after another.
  /// This is *melody*.
  const factory Music.seq(List<Music> elements) = Seq;

  /// Parallel composition: play these simultaneously.
  /// This is *harmony* and *texture*.
  const factory Music.par(List<Music> voices) = Par;

  // ---- Composition operators ----

  /// Sequential: `melody1 >> melody2` plays them in order.
  Music operator >>(Music next) => switch ((this, next)) {
    (Seq(elements: var a), Seq(elements: var b)) => Seq([...a, ...b]),
    (Seq(elements: var a), _) => Seq([...a, next]),
    (_, Seq(elements: var b)) => Seq([this, ...b]),
    _ => Seq([this, next]),
  };

  /// Parallel: `melody | bass` plays them at the same time.
  Music operator |(Music other) => switch ((this, other)) {
    (Par(voices: var a), Par(voices: var b)) => Par([...a, ...b]),
    (Par(voices: var a), _) => Par([...a, other]),
    (_, Par(voices: var b)) => Par([this, ...b]),
    _ => Par([this, other]),
  };

  // ---- Transformations ----

  /// Transpose every pitch by an interval.
  Music transpose(Interval interval) => switch (this) {
    Note(pitch: var p, duration: var d, expression: var e) =>
      Note(p + interval, d, expression: e),
    Rest() => this,
    Seq(elements: var es) => Seq(es.map((e) => e.transpose(interval)).toList()),
    Par(voices: var vs) => Par(vs.map((v) => v.transpose(interval)).toList()),
  };

  /// Reverse the temporal order (retrograde).
  Music get retrograde => switch (this) {
    Note() || Rest() => this,
    Seq(elements: var es) => Seq(es.reversed.map((e) => e.retrograde).toList()),
    Par(voices: var vs) => Par(vs.map((v) => v.retrograde).toList()),
  };

  /// Mirror pitches around a pivot (inversion).
  Music invert(Pitch pivot) => switch (this) {
    Note(pitch: var p, duration: var d, expression: var e) =>
      Note(_mirrorPitch(p, pivot), d, expression: e),
    Rest() => this,
    Seq(elements: var es) => Seq(es.map((e) => e.invert(pivot)).toList()),
    Par(voices: var vs) => Par(vs.map((v) => v.invert(pivot)).toList()),
  };

  /// Scale all durations by a factor (augmentation/diminution).
  Music scaleDurations(int numerator, int denominator) => switch (this) {
    Note(pitch: var p, duration: var d, expression: var e) =>
      Note(p, Duration(d.numerator * numerator, d.denominator * denominator), expression: e),
    Rest(duration: var d) =>
      Rest(Duration(d.numerator * numerator, d.denominator * denominator)),
    Seq(elements: var es) => Seq(es.map((e) => e.scaleDurations(numerator, denominator)).toList()),
    Par(voices: var vs) => Par(vs.map((v) => v.scaleDurations(numerator, denominator)).toList()),
  };

  /// Total duration of this music.
  Duration get totalDuration => switch (this) {
    Note(duration: var d) || Rest(duration: var d) => d,
    Seq(elements: var es) => es.fold(Duration(0, 1), (sum, e) => sum + e.totalDuration),
    Par(voices: var vs) => vs.map((v) => v.totalDuration).reduce(_maxDuration),
  };
}
```

### Layer 6: Higher-Level Concepts Built on the Core

Scales, chords, and keys aren't primitives — they're **patterns** that generate `Music`:

```dart
/// A scale is a sequence of intervals from a root.
/// It's a factory for melodies, not a thing you "play."
class Scale {
  final PitchClass tonic;
  final List<Interval> intervals;

  const Scale(this.tonic, this.intervals);

  /// Get the nth degree of this scale in a given octave.
  Pitch degree(int n, {int octave = 4}) { /* ... */ }

  /// Generate an ascending scale passage.
  Music ascending(int octave, Duration noteDuration) =>
      Music.seq([for (var i = 0; i < intervals.length; i++)
        Music.note(degree(i, octave: octave), noteDuration)]);

  static const major = [
    Interval.unison, Interval.majorSecond, Interval.majorThird,
    Interval.perfectFourth, Interval.perfectFifth, Interval.majorSixth,
    Interval.majorSeventh,
  ];

  static const minor = [/* ... */];
  static const dorian = [/* ... */];
  // Modes, pentatonic, blues, whole-tone, etc.
}

/// A chord as a set of intervals from a root.
/// Like Scale, it's a *pattern*, not a concrete sound.
class ChordType {
  final String name;
  final List<Interval> intervals;

  const ChordType(this.name, this.intervals);

  /// Realize this chord as parallel notes.
  Music realize(Pitch root, Duration duration, {Expression? expression}) =>
      Music.par([for (final iv in intervals)
        Music.note(root + iv, duration, expression: expression ?? const Expression())]);

  static const major = ChordType('major', [/* P1, M3, P5 */]);
  static const minor = ChordType('minor', [/* P1, m3, P5 */]);
  static const dominant7 = ChordType('dom7', [/* P1, M3, P5, m7 */]);
  // diminished, augmented, sus2, sus4, maj7, min7, etc.
}
```

### What It Looks Like In Practice

This is where the design pays off — **code that reads like a musical score**:

```dart
// Define some shorthand
const c4 = Pitch(PitchClass(NoteName.C), 4);
const e4 = Pitch(PitchClass(NoteName.E), 4);
const g4 = Pitch(PitchClass(NoteName.G), 4);
const q = Duration.quarter;
const e = Duration.eighth;
const h = Duration.half;

// A melody
final twinkleMelody = Music.seq([
  Music.note(c4, q), Music.note(c4, q),
  Music.note(g4, q), Music.note(g4, q),
  Music.note(a4, q), Music.note(a4, q),
  Music.note(g4, h),
]);

// Harmonize: melody with a bass line, simultaneously
final piece = twinkleMelody | bassLine;

// Twelve-tone row manipulation — retrograde inversion
final row = Music.seq([/* 12 notes */]);
final development = row >> row.retrograde >> row.invert(c4) >> row.retrograde.invert(c4);

// Build a chord progression
final progression = Music.seq([
  ChordType.major.realize(c4, h),     // I
  ChordType.minor.realize(a3, h),     // vi
  ChordType.major.realize(f3, h),     // IV
  ChordType.dominant7.realize(g3, h), // V7
]);

// Canon: the same melody, offset in time
final canon = twinkleMelody | (Music.rest(h) >> twinkleMelody.transpose(Interval.perfectFifth));
```

---

## Why This Design

**What I like about it:**

1. **Four constructors, infinite music.** The sealed `Music` type with `Note | Rest | Seq | Par` is the minimum viable set. Every musical structure — fugues, canons, chord progressions, polyrhythm — is just a particular tree shape. No special cases.

2. **Enharmonic awareness.** C♯ ≠ D♭. This matters for correct key signatures, interval spelling, and not lying about the music theory.

3. **Exact rational durations.** No floating-point drift. A dotted quarter is *exactly* 3/8. Triplets are *exactly* 1/12. Music is math, so we use math.

4. **Transformations are structural.** `transpose`, `retrograde`, `invert`, and `scaleDurations` operate on the tree. They're the four classic serial operations — but they work on *any* music, not just tone rows.

5. **Scales and chords are patterns, not data.** They're factories that *produce* `Music`, not a separate type system you have to integrate. This keeps the core tiny.

**What's intentionally missing:**

- **Timbre/instrumentation** — that's about *who plays it*, not *what's played*. Could add a `Music.annotate(String label, Music inner)` variant for this.
- **Tempo** — that's a performance concern. The structure represents *relative* time.
- **Barlines and time signatures** — these are visual/organizational, not structural. A `Meter` overlay could annotate a `Seq` without changing the tree.
- **Playback** — that's a separate concern entirely. A `MidiRenderer` or `LilypondExporter` would *consume* this tree, not be part of it.

Want me to actually build this out as a Dart package? I think it'd be a fun standalone library — and the sealed class pattern matching in Dart 3 makes the tree transformations genuinely elegant.

## The Problem: Your Mutex Scope Is Too Narrow

You have a **time-of-check-to-time-of-use (TOCTOU)** race condition. The mutex is protecting the wrong thing.

Here's what's likely happening:

```
Thread A: acquire mutex → read value → check condition → write → release mutex
Thread B: acquire mutex → read value → check condition → write → release mutex
```

You said the mutex is "per-operation" — meaning each step (read, check, write) is individually protected, but **the compound operation is not atomic**. So the actual interleaving is:

```
Thread A: [lock → read(x=0) → unlock]
Thread B: [lock → read(x=0) → unlock]    ← sees stale value!
Thread A: [lock → check(x==0? yes) → write(x=1) → unlock]
Thread B: [lock → check(x==0? yes) → write(x=1) → unlock]  ← duplicate write
```

Both threads read the same value, both pass the condition, both write.

## The Fix

The mutex must span the **entire** read-check-write sequence as a single critical section:

```
Thread A: lock → read → check → write → unlock
Thread B: .............(blocked).............. → lock → read → check → write → unlock
```

### Concretely

**Before (broken):**
```dart
Future<void> processOrder(String orderId) async {
  // Each call is individually "safe" but the sequence isn't
  final order = await _withLock(() => db.read(orderId));
  if (order.status == 'pending') {
    await _withLock(() => db.write(orderId, order.copyWith(status: 'processed')));
  }
}
```

**After (fixed):**
```dart
Future<void> processOrder(String orderId) async {
  await _withLock(() async {
    final order = await db.read(orderId);
    if (order.status == 'pending') {
      await db.write(orderId, order.copyWith(status: 'processed'));
    }
  });
}
```

## Deeper Considerations

**1. If this spans multiple servers**, an in-process mutex won't help at all. You need a **distributed lock** or push the atomicity into the database:

```sql
-- Atomic check-then-write: the WHERE clause IS the check
UPDATE orders SET status = 'processed'
WHERE id = $1 AND status = 'pending';
-- Check rows_affected == 1 to know if you "won"
```

This is almost always the better solution — it's simpler, survives process crashes, and eliminates the lock entirely.

**2. Optimistic concurrency** is another option: add a version column and use `WHERE version = $expected_version`. If someone else modified the row, your update affects 0 rows and you retry.

**3. Per-key locking** — if you're using a single global mutex, you're serializing *all* operations. Consider a lock-per-entity (e.g., keyed by `orderId`) so unrelated operations can proceed in parallel.

## The General Principle

A mutex protects an **invariant**, not an operation. Your invariant is "if the value is X, only one thread transitions it to Y." That invariant spans the read *and* the write — so the lock must too.

Here's a clean email validation function in Dart:

```dart
/// Validates whether [email] is a well-formed email address.
///
/// Checks RFC 5322 basics: non-empty local part, valid domain with at least
/// one dot, and no illegal characters. This intentionally avoids a monster
/// regex in favor of readability.
bool isValidEmail(String email) {
  // Split on '@' — there must be exactly one.
  final parts = email.split('@');
  if (parts.length != 2) return false;

  final local = parts[0];
  final domain = parts[1];

  // Local part: 1-64 chars, alphanumeric plus . _ % + -
  final localRegex = RegExp(r'^[a-zA-Z0-9._%+-]{1,64}$');
  if (!localRegex.hasMatch(local)) return false;

  // Domain: labels separated by dots, each 1-63 chars, TLD at least 2 chars.
  final labels = domain.split('.');
  if (labels.length < 2) return false;

  final labelRegex = RegExp(r'^[a-zA-Z0-9-]{1,63}$');
  for (final label in labels) {
    if (!labelRegex.hasMatch(label)) return false;
    if (label.startsWith('-') || label.endsWith('-')) return false;
  }

  // TLD must be at least 2 alphabetic characters.
  final tld = labels.last;
  if (tld.length < 2 || !RegExp(r'^[a-zA-Z]+$').hasMatch(tld)) return false;

  return true;
}
```

**Why this shape instead of a single regex?** A single RFC 5322 regex is ~6,000 characters of unreadable line noise. Breaking it into logical checks — split on `@`, validate local, validate each domain label, check the TLD — means someone can actually *read* it six months from now and understand what it accepts.

**What it catches:**
- Missing or multiple `@` signs
- Empty local part or domain
- Illegal characters in either part
- Domain labels starting/ending with hyphens
- Missing TLD or single-char TLDs (like `user@foo.x`)

**What it intentionally doesn't do:**
- Quoted local parts (`"weird stuff"@example.com`) — technically valid per RFC, almost never seen in practice
- IP address domains (`user@[192.168.1.1]`) — same story
- DNS lookup to verify the domain actually exists — that's a different concern (network vs. syntax)

For 99.9% of real-world email validation, this is the right trade-off between correctness and simplicity.
